Accelerated AI with P4 DPUs — Next-Level Flexibility, Performance & Scale on AMD AI NICs, presented by Shane Corban (AMD)

Shane Corban outlines AMD’s networking strategy for **scale-out** (and related) AI fabrics: **open systems** (UALink scale-up, **UEC** and **OCP** scale-out), **performance** through programmable hardware plus tight GPU–NIC software, and **flexibility** via **P4** so congestion and transport behavior can track rapid protocol changes. He contrasts **scale-up** (rack, load/store, loss-sensitive GPU memory traffic), **scale-out** (**RoCEv2** / **UEC RDMA**, large clusters, congestion/loss resilience), and **scale-across** (multi-site, uneven links, fairness).

**Polara** (400 G AI NIC, PCIe Gen 5, announced **OCP 3.0** form factor at the talk) is positioned as **P4-programmable**, **RoCEv2**- and **UEC**-capable, with claims of strong scale-out performance and multi-plane cost options. Software highlights include offloading **RoCE proxy**-style work from the CPU into P4 for higher **RoCE** transaction rates (slides cite ~10% vs. competition, ~8% training job gains in one Llama 3.1–style example), and **UEC** features such as **adaptive packet spray** across many paths with **in-order delivery** via placement metadata, plus **reactive congestion control** (**ECN** / **trim**) and **selective retransmission** versus go-back-N—summarized as large gains vs. baseline **RoCEv2** under loss and for peak throughput. **Multi-plane** designs split a 400 G port across independent switch planes to remove a core tier, with modeled **switch/port count** and **cost** reductions for very large GPU counts.

Roadmap touches **Helios** rack-scale architecture (**MI400**, **Venice** CPUs, six UAL switches, **72 GPU** scale-up domain, **UAL over Ethernet**), and **Volcano** **800 G** AI NIC (**Gen 6**, **UEC-ready**, 3 nm chip) with forward compatibility for Polara-era software innovations. Closing claims recap **UEC RDMA** vs. **RoCEv2**, reliability under loss, **multi-plane** savings, and open ecosystem alignment (**UAL**, **UEC**, **OCP**).
